For those who think it is 217... else if(3 * 317 / 100 > 243 / 100 * 464 / 100) It's great that you recognize integer division, but do not race to evaluate the division before multiplication. The expression on either side of the > should be evaluated left-to-right as multiplication and division share the same level of precedence. 243 / 100 * 464 / 100 2 * 464 / 100 928 / 100 9 is the reduced expression on the right side of the inequality, so we end with 9 > 9, or false

Using a precision modifier with an integer (%d) is okay--it will add leading zeroes, a different behavior than float-family values, but it will not work with a char (%c).

A student brought up an interesting point: There exists an assignment suppression character that could remove the need for any addresses to be listed. Some semesters require character input, and to be able to properly capture that character you may have written code such as scanf("%d", earlier_input); scanf(" %c", char_input); // note space before % An alternative method would be: scanf("%d", earlier_input); scanf("%*c"); // no address list here scanf("%c", char_input); // note space before % However, for this course you do not need to know this for exams, and the points for a correct answer were awarded for answer B.
